[2] Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Panama: 1st reports
Date: Wed 23 Jul 2008
Source: Bureau of Sugar Experimental Stations Australia (BSES) [edited]
<http://www.bses.org.au/news/2008/23July2008.pdf>


Orange rust spreads through Central America
-------------------------------------------
The sugarcane disease, orange rust, has been found in the Nicaragua, Costa
Rica, and Panama sugarcane regions of Central America. At a recent workshop
in Colombia, BSES senior researcher Dr Kathy Braithwaite, exchanged advice
and experience on the disease.

"The disease was first found in the Western Hemisphere in Florida in July
2007, and a short time later turned up in Guatemala -- now it is becoming a
serious threat in the Americas," Dr Braithwaite said. "It is not known how
orange rust arrived in the Americas but DNA fingerprinting currently under
way may identify its origin. The disease has not yet been seen in the
Caribbean or South America but is a serious concern to those sugar
industries," she said.

Orange rust fungus naturally occurs in the Asia-Pacific region and has been
present in Australia since the 1890s. Australia had success fighting the
disease by using resistant varieties. "It was estimated that orange rust
caused direct and indirect losses of up to AUD 400 [million] [approx. USD
334 million] in Australia in 2000 and losses continued for up to 3-4 years
as growers went through the expensive exercise of replacing the highly
susceptible variety Q124. Similar losses could occur in other countries
when orange rust arrives but this will depend on the susceptibility of
their varieties and the environmental suitability for orange rust," Dr
Braithwaite said.

The international plant pathology workshop highlighted that strains of
sugarcane rust can adapt and a previously resistant sugarcane variety can
become susceptible again. This highlights the dangers of over-reliance on
one variety and the need for continual vigilance regarding the possible
reappearance of old diseases.

