[3] USA (Louisiana): alert
Date: Tue 5 Aug 2008
Source: Delta Farm Press [edited]
<http://deltafarmpress.com/news/sugarcane-rust-0805/>


Rust threatening Louisiana sugarcane
------------------------------------
New sugarcane varieties are increasing yields, but diseases pose a constant
threat, farmers were told by LSU [Louisiana State University] AgCenter
researchers at a recent sugarcane field day at St Martinville, Louisiana.
Researchers told farmers that developing new varieties is an ongoing
effort. "Trying to stay one step ahead of rust is getting to be quite an
ordeal," said Ken Gravois, LSU AgCenter sugarcane breeder.

Orange rust disease affecting sugarcane was found in Florida cane fields
during 2007, Jeff Hoy, LSU AgCenter pathologist, said. Louisiana growers
could be finding it soon. "We are anticipating it is going to show up this
year [2008] or the next," Hoy said. He said preliminary variety resistance
evaluations are being conducted for orange rust in Florida.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Orange rust of sugarcane is caused by the fungus _Puccinia kuehnii_.
Symptoms include minute, elongated yellow lesions, which develop an orange
to orange-brown colour as they expand. Most rust pustules occur on the
lower leaf surface with more lesions toward the leaf base. Environmental
conditions conducive for the development of orange rust include warm, humid
summers and cool autumns, and the disease is favoured by rain. The disease
has the potential to cause significant economic losses to sugarcane crops.
A related species, _P. melanocephala_, causes brown or common rust. Colour
and distribution of leaf lesions varies from orange rust, and development
of this pathogen is inhibited by rain. Both rusts are rapidly spread by
wind, and disease management includes fungicide treatments and development
of resistant cane varieties suitable to local requirements.

In Australia the pathogen had been present for 100 years without causing
significant losses until in 2000 a much more virulent strain emerged
devastating the most widely grown sugarcane cultivar and demonstrating once
again the dangers of monoculture. A similar occurrence would be one
possible explanation for the emergence of orange rust in the Americas, or
the pathogen may have bee introduced recently. DNA fingerprinting of
different isolates mentioned in item [2] should help to clarify this question.

